  "prompt": "What is the nicest library at Columbia to work at?",
  "response": "Columbia University offers several libraries, each with its own unique features and atmosphere. The \"nicest\" library largely depends on personal preferences and specific needs. However, one of the most popular and well-regarded libraries at Columbia is Butler Library.\n\n1. **Butler Library**: \n   - **Architecture**: Impressive and iconic, combining classic and modern design elements.\n   - **Facilities**: Comprehensive resources including quiet study rooms, computer labs, and extensive collections.\n   - **Ambiance**: Known for its academic atmosphere that fosters concentration and productivity.\n   - **24-hour Access**: Allows students to study late into the night, which is crucial during exam periods.\n\n2. **Lehman Social Sciences Library**:\n   - **Focus**: Ideal for students in social sciences.\n   - **Setting**: Offers a quieter, less crowded environment compared to Butler, with good study spaces.\n\n3. **Avery Architectural & Fine Arts Library**:\n   - **Specialization**: Best suited for students in architecture and fine arts majors.\n   - **Collections**: Houses one of the finest collections in these fields.\n\n4. **Science & Engineering Library**:\n   - **Focus**: Tailored to students in science and engineering disciplines.\n   - **Modernity**: Offers state-of-the-art facilities and collaborative workspaces.\n\n5. **Business and Economics Library** (Uris Hall):\n   - **Target Audience**: Perfect for business students needing access to economic and business resources.\n\nUltimately, try visiting a few different libraries to see which environment suits your study style best. All Columbia libraries have unique strengths, so it's worth exploring them to find your ideal study spot.",
